Hosting Angular & .NET app on Windows VPS and IIS

Recently, I decided to get a Windows VPS to play around with and migrate my projects that I hosted on various platforms. First thing that was to migrate was this blog.

Unfortunately, through light Google research I failed to find a comprehensive guide which would take me step by step to this up.

I talked to my bro who is a genius in this domain and eventually found that it is quite simple to host on IIS.

Setting up Windows VPS

First things first, the Windows Server requires installation of IIS. This shall be done via Server Manager. Just add a new role (IIS Services role) via Server Manager.

Angular

Angular app needs to be published. This can be done by focusing on the main project folder and executing build command.

ng build –-prod

After the build is finished a new folder will appear in the .\project_name folder. The folder’s name is dist. This folder should be copied to the VPS, which can be done by accessing the \\IP Address\c$ via file explorer. The credentials windows will be prompted and after entering them, just copy the dist folder to C:\inetpub\wwwroot location. Rename the dist folder to the project-frontend and the deployment of Angular app is finished.

.NET

Similarly to the frontend, we’ll need to publish the backend app. .NET does things a bit differently than Angular.

What you want to do is open up a PowerShell and navigate to your projects folder

cd <project’s root folder location>

Right after run:

dotnet publish

After publish is finished a new “publish” folder will appear at <project_location>\bin\Debug\net6.0. This folder should be copied to the VPS in the same manner as Angular dist folder and to the same location. Also, this folder’s name should be changed to project-backend and after that we can consider deployment of .NET app to be finished.

IIS URL Rewrite

In order to enable Angular app to run smoothly it’s recommended to install this module. After downloading it (https://www.iis.net/downloads/microsoft/url-rewrite) and installing it on the VPS, restart the IIS and a new icon should appear when overviewing a website.

Inside of URL Rewrite you should add a blank inbound rule and then populate the fields as in the following pictures:
